ps as future archives? What kinds of interplay is there between archives and literature? And what is the basis for genres such as the archive novel, the blog novel, and docufiction? The contributions by renowned cultural studies scholars in this volume use examples to show how literature and archives encounter one another.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aArchival resources. 0aAuthorsxArchives. 4aArchiv. 4aDokufiktion. 4aNachlass. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh  aArchive.  adocufiction.  aestate.1 aBüscher, Nick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDallinger, Petra-Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHofer, Georg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKastberger, Klaus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKastberger, Klaus, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMittermayer, Manfred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNeuhuber, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNeuhuber, Christian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNeundlinger, Helmut, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPiok, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchneider, Steffen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUlrich, Carmen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWolf, Burkhardt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZeisberg, 